Uh...

248
00:10:10,166 --> 00:10:12,458
[DARU groans, sighs]

249
00:10:14,166 --> 00:10:15,375
[OKABE sighs]

250
00:10:18,041 --> 00:10:19,708
[creaking]

251
00:10:19,791 --> 00:10:20,791
Uh--

252
00:10:23,583 --> 00:10:24,583
[gasps]

253
00:10:26,708 --> 00:10:27,583
[BOTH gasp, groan]

254
00:10:27,666 --> 00:10:28,750
[thud]

255
00:10:28,833 --> 00:10:29,833
--[MAYURI gasps]
--Kyouma?

256
00:10:29,916 --> 00:10:31,083
[RUKA]
Are you okay?

257
00:10:31,166 --> 00:10:34,416
[OKABE, SUZUHA groaning]

258
00:10:34,500 --> 00:10:35,541
[SUZUHA gasps]

259
00:10:35,625 --> 00:10:38,041
Oh, hi, Suzu.

260
00:10:38,125 --> 00:10:41,250
Um, hey, there! [chuckles]

261
00:10:48,708 --> 00:10:50,333
[BOTH]
Ta-da!

262
00:10:50,416 --> 00:10:51,208
[YUKI giggles]

263
00:10:51,291 --> 00:10:52,375
So pretty!

264
00:10:52,458 --> 00:10:53,625
[FARIS]
Meow!

265
00:10:53,708 --> 00:10:54,791
[DARU]
It's a feast for my eyes

266
00:10:54,875 --> 00:10:56,458
and I'm about to
order seconds, girl!

267
00:10:56,541 --> 00:10:57,875
[YUKI giggles]

268
00:10:57,958 --> 00:10:59,625
Hey, where did Okarin go?

269
00:10:59,708 --> 00:11:02,208
He went up to the roof
with Suzuha earlier.

270
00:11:02,291 --> 00:11:05,125
Seemed like they wanted to
talk about something important.

271
00:11:05,208 --> 00:11:06,541
Oh, okay.

272
00:11:12,708 --> 00:11:14,125
[OKABE] You didn't have
to come up with a lie

273
00:11:14,208 --> 00:11:16,041
in the first place, you know.

274
00:11:16,125 --> 00:11:18,625
Saying you're his little
sister complicates things.

275
00:11:18,708 --> 00:11:20,416
Makes you more suspicious.

276
00:11:20,500 --> 00:11:22,708
[SUZUHA] I get that,
but how was I supposed to know

277
00:11:22,791 --> 00:11:24,916
that Mom would wanna
hang out with me so much?

278
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:27,583
[OKABE] We should've had a plan
before Daru and Yuki met.

279
00:11:27,666 --> 00:11:29,833
[SUZUHA]
That day at Summer ComiMa.

280
00:11:29,916 --> 00:11:31,875
Who knew she'd be one of
Mayu's cosplay friends

281
00:11:31,958 --> 00:11:33,208
before she'd ever met Dad?

282
00:11:33,291 --> 00:11:34,583
--[thud]
--[YUKI, DARU gasp]

283
00:11:34,666 --> 00:11:37,500
Ow, ow, ow, ow! Huh?

284
00:11:41,916 --> 00:11:43,125
Huh?

285
00:11:43,208 --> 00:11:45,250
[SUZUHA]
And suddenly, there she was.

286
00:11:45,333 --> 00:11:47,708
[sputtering]

287
00:11:47,791 --> 00:11:51,416
[OKABE] She has no idea that one
day she'll give birth to you.

288
00:11:51,500 --> 00:11:52,833
I wonder if she
feels a connection

289
00:11:52,916 --> 00:11:54,833
even if she can't
quite place it.

290
00:11:57,708 --> 00:12:00,333
[SUZUHA] Dad said he'll explain
everything sooner or later.

291
00:12:00,416 --> 00:12:02,375
When the time's right.

292
00:12:02,458 --> 00:12:03,291
[OKABE]
Hm.

293
00:12:03,375 --> 00:12:04,625
Still though,

294
00:12:04,708 --> 00:12:06,666
it's hard to believe they'll
have a kid together.

295
00:12:08,166 --> 00:12:09,125
Well, get used to it,

296
00:12:09,208 --> 00:12:10,416
because the fact
that I'm still here

297
00:12:10,500 --> 00:12:13,458
means the future
hasn't changed at all.

298
00:12:13,541 --> 00:12:15,958
[jet engine roaring]

299
00:12:16,041 --> 00:12:17,333
[SUZUHA gasps]

300
00:12:19,958 --> 00:12:21,833
[sighs]

301
00:12:21,916 --> 00:12:24,000
[SUZUHA]
This world's so peaceful.

302
00:12:26,208 --> 00:12:28,833
[SUZUHA]
No one knows to be scared.

303
00:12:28,916 --> 00:12:30,916
By the time I was grown up,

304
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:34,125
you'd only see scenes like
these in photos and old movies.

305
00:12:34,208 --> 00:12:36,125
[OKABE] World War III
ravages everything.

306
00:12:36,208 --> 00:12:37,875
[SUZUHA] Yeah, and because
Dad and the others

307
00:12:37,958 --> 00:12:39,083
were building a time machine,

308
00:12:39,166 --> 00:12:41,666
we were seen as
a rebel organization.

309
00:12:41,750 --> 00:12:42,750
[OKABE]
At least you and your parents

310
00:12:42,833 --> 00:12:45,250
managed to escape alive somehow.

311
00:12:45,333 --> 00:12:47,333
[SUZUHA]
No, my Mom was mowed down

312
00:12:47,416 --> 00:12:49,208
in a barrage of bullets
trying to protect me

313
00:12:49,291 --> 00:12:51,125
--[OKABE gasps]
--from a military drone.

314
00:12:54,625 --> 00:12:55,916
[sighs]

315
00:12:56,000 --> 00:12:59,250
I saw her body ripped to
shreds right before my eyes.

316
00:12:59,333 --> 00:13:02,000
I was practically
showered in her blood.

317
00:13:05,541 --> 00:13:07,708
Uncle Okarin?

318
00:13:07,791 --> 00:13:11,583
The future in store for this
world line is a living hell.

319
00:13:13,500 --> 00:13:16,083
[SUZUHA] So many countries start
fighting over time machines

320
00:13:16,166 --> 00:13:18,416
that the death toll
is unfathomable.

321
00:13:18,500 --> 00:13:21,375
There are decades of
horror and despair ahead!

322
00:13:21,458 --> 00:13:24,458
We're talking about the lives
of billions of people here!

323
00:13:24,541 --> 00:13:25,833
You can change it!

324
00:13:25,916 --> 00:13:27,041
[OKABE gasping]

325
00:13:27,125 --> 00:13:28,833
I am begging you.

326
00:13:28,916 --> 00:13:31,833
Please. Please...

327
00:13:31,916 --> 00:13:32,791
[OKABE]
I can't.

328
00:13:32,875 --> 00:13:34,541
[gasps] Uncle!

329
00:13:34,625 --> 00:13:36,583
[OKABE] I've drifted through
so many different world lines

330
00:13:36,666 --> 00:13:37,875
that I've lost count.

331
00:13:37,958 --> 00:13:39,125
[SUZUHA gasps]

332
00:13:39,208 --> 00:13:40,208
[OKABE]
The one constant is that

333
00:13:40,291 --> 00:13:42,041
no matter what
reality I step into,

334
00:13:42,125 --> 00:13:44,083
time machines destroy lives.

335
00:13:44,166 --> 00:13:46,916
I've seen them drive you
to ruin, too, damn it!

336
00:13:47,000 --> 00:13:48,375
Over and over.

337
00:13:48,458 --> 00:13:49,916
Loops of misery.

338
00:13:50,000 --> 00:13:53,250
Believe me, I know how useless
someone can be against time!

339
00:13:54,458 --> 00:13:56,750
[OKABE]
No matter what I tried...

340
00:13:56,833 --> 00:13:58,708
...I was powerless.

341
00:13:58,791 --> 00:14:01,833
You say that, but you have
altered world lines before.

342
00:14:01,916 --> 00:14:04,208
You told me that yourself.

343
00:14:04,291 --> 00:14:06,458
So then... why not?

344
00:14:06,541 --> 00:14:07,916
[OKABE]
It won't work!

345
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:10,416
You can't just change the
past to switch world lines!

346
00:14:10,500 --> 00:14:13,375
It breaks the fundamental rules
that govern our universe.

347
00:14:13,458 --> 00:14:16,375
Humans like us were never meant
to tamper with such powers.

348
00:14:16,458 --> 00:14:19,250
The moment we start
meddling, we're punished!

349
00:14:19,333 --> 00:14:20,625
It's too much!

350
00:14:20,708 --> 00:14:23,083
I'd rather tear my eyes out
than see it all again!

351
00:14:23,166 --> 00:14:24,750
Only you can do it.

352
00:14:24,833 --> 00:14:28,208
[OKABE panting]

353
00:14:31,666 --> 00:14:33,333
[SUZUHA]
We still have some time.

354
00:14:35,333 --> 00:14:38,375
Please give it another
thought, for me!

355
00:14:38,458 --> 00:14:39,458
This isn't over.

356
00:14:39,541 --> 00:14:42,000
--[door opens]
--I haven't given up.

357
00:14:42,083 --> 00:14:43,083
[door slams]

358
00:14:44,666 --> 00:14:47,375
[MAYURI] I guess Suzu had other
stuff she needed to do, huh?

359
00:14:47,458 --> 00:14:48,916
[OKABE]
Yeah.

360
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:51,500
The two of you didn't fight
up there on the roof, did you?

361
00:14:51,583 --> 00:14:53,916
[OKABE]
That's not what happened.

362
00:14:54,000 --> 00:14:55,375
[MAYURI]
I see.

363
00:14:55,458 --> 00:14:59,000
Ooh! I didn't think it was
gonna be this chilly today.

364
00:15:04,291 --> 00:15:06,750
[MAYURI] At least the lab
was lively for a change.

365
00:15:06,833 --> 00:15:09,166
It was a lot of fun
seeing everyone.

366
00:15:09,250 --> 00:15:10,375
Is that right?

367
00:15:10,458 --> 00:15:11,791
Yep!

368
00:15:11,875 --> 00:15:12,875
To be honest with you,

369
00:15:12,958 --> 00:15:14,583
for some reason,
I've felt really lonely

370
00:15:14,666 --> 00:15:16,750
every time I've gone
over there lately.

371
00:15:16,833 --> 00:15:18,875
It's been sad.

372
00:15:18,958 --> 00:15:20,583
[OKABE]
Even though Daru's there?

373
00:15:20,666 --> 00:15:21,625
[MAYURI]
Yeah.

374
00:15:21,708 --> 00:15:23,041
And it's strange,
because before,

375
00:15:23,125 --> 00:15:25,208
I used to wait in the lab
all by myself for you,

376
00:15:25,291 --> 00:15:27,666
so I should be used to that.

377
00:15:27,750 --> 00:15:30,583
There's no reason for me
to feel alone when I'm there.

378
00:15:30,666 --> 00:15:32,291
But it's just...

379
00:15:32,375 --> 00:15:35,666
Sometimes it's so overwhelming
that it makes me want to cry.

380
00:15:35,750 --> 00:15:37,416
--[OKABE gasps]
--Big ugly tears, you know?

381
00:15:37,500 --> 00:15:38,750
Kind of feels like
there used to be

382
00:15:38,833 --> 00:15:41,125
a bunch more people
hanging around.

383
00:15:42,250 --> 00:15:43,083
[OKABE]
It's an illusion.

384
00:15:43,166 --> 00:15:44,416
Huh?

385
00:15:44,500 --> 00:15:45,583
[OKABE]
Just a dream.

386
00:15:46,625 --> 00:15:47,541
[OKABE]
There were only three people

387
00:15:47,625 --> 00:15:48,750
that ever came to the lab.

388
00:15:48,833 --> 00:15:51,875
You and me, and Daru
at the computer.

389
00:15:53,208 --> 00:15:55,750
[MAYURI]
Hmm, I guess you're right.

390
00:15:57,916 --> 00:15:59,500
[phone vibrates]

391
00:16:03,958 --> 00:16:06,166
[MAYURI]
Is it a bad message?

392
00:16:06,250 --> 00:16:09,208
[OKABE] No. Some people from
Viktor Chondria University

393
00:16:09,291 --> 00:16:11,750
are giving a seminar
in Akiba tomorrow.

394
00:16:11,833 --> 00:16:14,041
I was hoping to talk with
one of their professors,

395
00:16:14,125 --> 00:16:17,083
but I guess they've gone
out drinking for the night.

396
00:16:17,166 --> 00:16:19,333
[MAYURI gasps]
So weird!

397
00:16:19,416 --> 00:16:22,250
It's like you're
totally normal now.

398
00:16:22,333 --> 00:16:24,166
I'll be perfectly
fine by myself.

399
00:16:24,250 --> 00:16:25,916
Go meet them!

400
00:16:26,000 --> 00:16:27,041
[OKABE]
Okay.

401
00:16:27,125 --> 00:16:28,583
Sorry for ditching you.

402
00:16:46,916 --> 00:16:51,875
[chattering]

403
00:16:55,625 --> 00:16:58,750
[OKABE] Artificial
Intelligence Revolution.

404
00:16:58,833 --> 00:17:01,000
Viktor Chondria University.

405
00:17:01,083 --> 00:17:03,208
Professor Alexis Leskinen.

406
00:17:09,166 --> 00:17:12,583
[OKABE]
It's... the college she went to.

407
00:17:16,500 --> 00:17:18,666
[MAKISE]
I'm so scared.

408
00:17:18,750 --> 00:17:21,000
I think I'm dying.

409
00:17:21,083 --> 00:17:23,125
But... I don't want to die!

410
00:17:23,208 --> 00:17:29,166
[OKABE gasping]

411
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:37,041
[OKABE screaming]

412
00:17:37,125 --> 00:17:41,291
[gagging]

413
00:17:42,708 --> 00:17:48,125
[OKABE panting]

414
00:18:05,166 --> 00:18:07,333
[MAHO]
Hey. Excuse me.

415
00:18:09,666 --> 00:18:10,833
[MAHO]
You work here, right?

416
00:18:10,916 --> 00:18:13,250
[OKABE]
Uh--huh?

417
00:18:13,333 --> 00:18:15,750
Which way do I go to
get to the staff room?

418
00:18:15,833 --> 00:18:17,166
Uh...

419
00:18:19,166 --> 00:18:20,791
--[MAHO] Hmm?
--[OKABE] Uh...

420
00:18:20,875 --> 00:18:22,041
Oh, you must be lost.

421
00:18:22,125 --> 00:18:24,750
This is a university-level
conference.

422
00:18:24,833 --> 00:18:26,416
I'm well aware, you idiot!

423
00:18:26,500 --> 00:18:27,625
[OKABE stammers]

424
00:18:27,708 --> 00:18:28,708
[MAHO sighs]
It's the same thing every time.

425
00:18:28,791 --> 00:18:29,791
[OKABE]
What do you mean?

426
00:18:29,875 --> 00:18:31,041
You're the fourth
person to tell me

427
00:18:31,125 --> 00:18:33,708
I'm in the wrong place
since I arrived here.

428
00:18:33,791 --> 00:18:36,208
"Viktor Chondria University."

429
00:18:36,291 --> 00:18:38,625
Part of the Brain
Science Institute.

430
00:18:38,708 --> 00:18:40,500
Oh, I get it. You're
returning someone's--

431
00:18:40,583 --> 00:18:42,875
Ugh! Fourth time for that, too!

432
00:18:42,958 --> 00:18:43,916
[MAHO grunts]

433
00:18:45,500 --> 00:18:47,208
[OKABE] Wait, you're telling me
the school is letting in...

434
00:18:48,375 --> 00:18:49,375
...middle schoolers?

435
00:18:49,458 --> 00:18:50,916
[MAHO]
Now you're just being insulting!

436
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:54,208
There's no university that
accepts people that young!

437
00:18:54,291 --> 00:18:56,500
[OKABE]
You're 21 years old?

438
00:18:56,583 --> 00:18:58,916
[MAHO] In other words,
I'm a full-grown woman!

439
00:18:59,000 --> 00:19:03,083
Not in middle school,
elementary school, or preschool!

440
00:19:03,166 --> 00:19:04,250
You got that?

441
00:19:04,333 --> 00:19:06,666
But--sure.

442
00:19:08,416 --> 00:19:09,291
[OKABE]
I was in the wrong.

443
00:19:09,375 --> 00:19:10,541
[gasps]

444
00:19:10,625 --> 00:19:12,375
[OKABE]
I'm sorry.

445
00:19:12,458 --> 00:19:14,333
[MAHO scoffs]
Yeah, okay, whatever.

446
00:19:14,416 --> 00:19:17,458
It's always like this,
no matter what country I go to.

447
00:19:17,541 --> 00:19:18,500
[OKABE]
Shocking.

448
00:19:18,583 --> 00:19:19,666
What was that?

449
00:19:19,750 --> 00:19:21,541
[OKABE]
Uh, nothing! Just a cough.

450
00:19:21,625 --> 00:19:22,791
[sighs]

451
00:19:23,916 --> 00:19:25,625
[OKABE]
Uh, wrong direction.

452
00:19:25,708 --> 00:19:27,791
You want the staff room?
Go out that way,

453
00:19:27,875 --> 00:19:29,958
and then it's the door
at the end of the hall.

454
00:19:33,875 --> 00:19:35,250
Thanks for the help.

455
00:19:37,166 --> 00:19:38,916
[OKABE]
Twenty-one, huh?

456
00:19:39,000 --> 00:19:40,791
I can practically
hear Daru shouting,

457
00:19:40,875 --> 00:19:42,791
"Legal loli for the win!"

458
00:19:43,833 --> 00:19:44,791
[gasps]

459
00:19:46,458 --> 00:19:49,250
[OKABE]
That's... Kiryuu Moeka!

460
00:19:51,791 --> 00:19:53,583
[OKABE]
Why...?

461
00:19:53,666 --> 00:19:55,416
What is she doing here?

462
00:19:56,500 --> 00:19:58,666
[OKABE]
No. Not again!

463
00:19:58,750 --> 00:19:59,958
Calm down.

464
00:20:00,041 --> 00:20:01,791
This is the beta world line.

465
00:20:01,875 --> 00:20:03,666
It's nothing like the other one.

466
00:20:05,041 --> 00:20:06,291
[OKABE]
It can't be.

467
00:20:10,916 --> 00:20:13,875
[applause]

468
00:20:13,958 --> 00:20:15,250
[OKABE gasps]

469
00:20:15,333 --> 00:20:16,291
[OKABE]
It's...

470
00:20:17,500 --> 00:20:19,000
[OKABE]
...that girl.

471
00:20:23,166 --> 00:20:24,416
Good day, everyone.

472
00:20:24,500 --> 00:20:26,416
[MAHO speaking Japanese]

473
00:20:26,500 --> 00:20:28,875
[ALEXIS] Thank you for
attending my seminar.

474
00:20:28,958 --> 00:20:31,666
I am Alexis Leskinen from
Viktor Chondria University's

475
00:20:31,750 --> 00:20:34,041
Brain Science Institute.

476
00:20:34,125 --> 00:20:37,458
This is my interpreter
and assistant, Hiyajo Maho.

477
00:20:37,541 --> 00:20:41,291
[speaking Japanese]

478
00:20:41,375 --> 00:20:43,000
[applause]

479
00:20:43,083 --> 00:20:44,958
The topic of today's
seminar is broad.

480
00:20:45,041 --> 00:20:46,500
[MAHO in English]
The topic of today's seminar

481
00:20:46,583 --> 00:20:48,833
is the artificial
intelligence revolution.

482
00:20:48,916 --> 00:20:51,041
But before we delve
too much into that,

483
00:20:51,125 --> 00:20:54,083
there's a thesis I'd like
to familiarize you with.

484
00:20:55,250 --> 00:20:58,041
[MAHO] This paper was published
by a brilliant female researcher

485
00:20:58,125 --> 00:21:00,375
from our university laboratory.

486
00:21:00,458 --> 00:21:03,125
All of our memories are stored
within the cerebral cortex.

487
00:21:03,208 --> 00:21:04,458
More specifically,

488
00:21:04,541 --> 00:21:06,708
our histories are held
within the temporal lobe.

489
00:21:06,791 --> 00:21:09,750
Our minds work as if they have
a computer's flash memory.

490
00:21:09,833 --> 00:21:11,375
The brain sends
electrical signals

491
00:21:11,458 --> 00:21:13,958
between neurons at
lightning-fast rates.

492
00:21:14,041 --> 00:21:17,125
Ultimately, it is the pattern
of these electrical signals

493
00:21:17,208 --> 00:21:19,208
which create and
reinforce memories.

494
00:21:19,291 --> 00:21:21,291
They archive our pasts.

495
00:21:27,083 --> 00:21:28,583
[MAHO] I regret to say
that the bright woman

496
00:21:28,666 --> 00:21:30,000
who proposed this theory

497
00:21:30,083 --> 00:21:33,125
passed away at the
young age of 18.

498
00:21:33,208 --> 00:21:35,083
But using her theory
as a foundation,

499
00:21:35,166 --> 00:21:38,291
